<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-514-664  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 514 664.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  August 7 1989 v217 n7 p38(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Are the skies friendly for fiber optic cable? (the growing use ofaerial fiber)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pope, Daniel L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Some engineers find it difficult to understand why cablesuspension strand that is strong enough to support heavy coppercable is inadequate for supporting smaller, lighter, fiber opticcable.andP;  Glass conductors are brittle and will fail under stress,requiring the limitation of tensile strain in designing an aerialfiber plant.andP;  An aerial plant must be able to carry its load, butit must be based on the concept of limiting the elastic strain inthe glass fibers.andP;  An aerial fiber optic plant must be strongenough to keep the strain in the fibers within acceptable limitsunder prescribed loads and able to support the conductor loadsgiven in NESC Rule 250B without exceeding the allowable force inthe support strand.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CablesSystem DesignTelephone SystemsFiber opticsTelecommunication systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablemap.andO;Caption:   Typical stringing tensions. (table)General loading map with respect to loading of overhead lines.andO;(map)maximum permissible aerial span lengths. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>